{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510122"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:24:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:24:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11497"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11497"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.12,0.25,0.51,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4128"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115491"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4128"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11497"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97494"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2936"},{"type":"tags","id":"3032"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5119"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16176"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49157"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115491"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents with her son to see her General Practitioner with a four-week history of difficulty falling asleep, tossing and turning for approximately two hours before falling asleep. She reports sleeping for only four to five hours a night and blames it on her \u0027body clock\u0027 waking as early as 5am. Her husband died of a cardiac arrest six weeks ago, with her sleep issues starting two weeks after his death. Her son reports that he hears his mother weeping silently in her bedroom, and at times loud laughter. She states that she occasionally hears her husband\u0027s voice at night, and he appears in her dreams nearly every day. She feels sad about his death, reminiscing good times spent with him, stating \u003Cem\u003E\u0022Those memories are the only thing keeping me sane\u003C/em\u003E\u0022. She seemed defensive when asked about \u0027feeling depressed\u0027 or self-harm ideation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has lost 4 kg over the past month and is not cooking as much as usual for herself and the grandchildren. She has also stopped attending her weekly social gatherings with her friends but is still able to perform her activities of daily living independently (ADLs). On examination, she appears alert and oriented. A neurological examination revealed no abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute stress disorder","Major depressive disorder","Adjustment disorder","Normal bereavement and grief","Schizoaffective disorder"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal bereavement and grief\u003C/strong\u003E is a normal occurrence that happens after an individual experiences a tragic life event, such as the death of a relative. Individuals going through normal bereavement usually experience pangs of grief associated with thoughts or reminders of the deceased that can occur very sporadically. Similar to this patient, emptiness and loss is a common feeling associated with occasional pleasant emotions. Individuals experiencing grief experience some depressive symptoms such as sleep disturbances, social withdrawal, and anhedonia. Mild hallucinations such as hearing the voice of the deceased, and visions or dreams of the deceased are all normal occurrences in grieving individuals, and should not be confused with a psychotic disorder. Symptoms of normal grief progressively improve and resolve within six to twelve months. Loss of appetite and associated weight loss is a common symptom in normal bereavement and grief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECaution must be met not to diagnose \u003Cstrong\u003Emajor depressive disorder\u003C/strong\u003E in this patient. While there is evidence of depressive symptoms in this patient, she does not fulfil all the DSM-5 criteria for a major depressive disorder such as feelings of worthlessness or guilt, suicidal ideation, lack of focus, and psychomotor retardation. In addition, cognition in grief focuses on memories (good, bad) of the deceased person whereas in major depressive disorder the cognitions are of hopelessness, worthlessness, pointlessness, and other forms of negativity about oneself and the future.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdjustment disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is described as emotional or behavioural symptoms, commonly associated with depressed mood that develops within two to three months of a stressful event. Such behavioural symptoms usually also have a significant impairment in activities of daily living, not seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute stress disorder\u003C/strong\u003E may often mimic normal grief. Acute stress disorder is usually precipitated by an emotionally intense event, such as the death of a loved one. It is commonly associated with flashbacks from triggering stimuli and a heightened sense of awareness, such as hypervigilance. While this patient experienced a tragic and traumatic event, she does not have any hypervigilance or intense flashbacks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchizoaffective disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by symptoms of both schizophrenia and mood disorders. This patient does not exhibit the chronic psychotic symptoms or the mood disorder symptoms required for this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Normal grief reaction typically resolves within 12 months."],"references":["Prigerson HG, Boelen PA, Xu J, et al. Validation of the new DSM-5-TR criteria for prolonged grief disorder and the PG-13-Revised (PG-13-R) scale. World Psychiatry 2021; 20:96. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33432758/","Lobb EA, Kristjanson LJ, Aoun SM, et al. Predictors of complicated grief: a systematic review of empirical studies. Death Stud 2010; 34:673. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24482845/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97494"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11497"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97494"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T08:42:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T08:44:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4128"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115491"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":nul